title: For Sale/Trade:  1943 Mosin Nagant Tula CH or CN Marked
postcontent:
For sale is a 1943 Tula M91/30.  It was tested and marked as passing sniper accuracy but was never drilled and scoped to be a sniper rifle (No plugged holes).  You can clearly see a "C" stamped over the top point of the Tula star but can only see the left vertical of the "H or N."   These marks mean that it passed accuracy testing to be a sniper.   Some other interesting markings on the barrel shank and on the high-wall part of the receiver.  The bore is very good and not counter-bored.  I have never fired this rifle..  Post war stock with cool toe-splice.  It is force-matched.  If my research is correct the cleaning rod is Romanian. It comes with a non-matching bayonet that is very snug and hard to mount. It is a really good example of a Tula made rifle built at the height of the Great Patriotic war.  The finish is much better than the current crop of refurbished rifles coming these days (IMO).  Beware, when you buy one they tend to multiply!

title: For Sale:  1816 Type III, Harpers Ferry, Smoothbore flintlock musket, Manufactured 1831. Percussion, "Belgian cone", .69 cal.
postcontent:
This has been in my Family for over 50 years, and been hanging on a wall. I'm pricing this right, to go to a good home, hopefully to someone who'll actually shoot it!

This is an original condition, authentic, model 1816 type III Harper's Ferry musket; manufactured in 1831. This one has been in the same family for 50 years, Above Average Condition and Original conver.

Overall length; 55in.

The Model 1816 was originally designed as a flintlock muzzleloader, iron buttplate is straight against the shoulder, iron strap opposite the lock, iron trigger guard, no rear sight, one iron barrel band, one strap hook, and forward sight. Original wooden ramrod in place below the barrel. The butt stock features a very low comb, which is the graceful curve between the butt and the wrist of the stock. Manufactured by Harpers Ferry Armory, Harpers Ferry Virginia (now WV) from 1816 through 1844. Most were converted to percussion in the 1850's, this one by the "Belgian cone" method, this alteration was performed at the Arsenal. The flintlock pan was milled flat to the lock, the void filled with brass and the top milled flush with the lock, the flintlock hole was plugged, a nipple lug was placed on top of the barrel slightly to the side of lock, and a new hammer was placed to achieve the correct alignment. Lock is marked "HARPERS / FERRY / 1831" behind the hammer, with eagle head and "US" in front. Round barrel length 40in. This is an authentic Harpers Ferry Model 1816, NOT a reproduction. Above Average Arsenal Version.

This particular gun comes with a powderhorn, but that item is not the original powderhorn.

Price: $800.00
